2025-12-04 16:05:28,098 — INFO — LMM results table added to report
Number of features analyzed: 50
Features where LMM succeeded: 50
Features using fallback (OLS or skipped): 0
LMM diagnostics notes (top):
succeeded_LMM: 50
Histogram of ICC (proportion of variance explained by batch):
Intraclass Correlation Coefficient (ICC) is the ratio of variance due to batch effects to the total variance (batch + residual). 
It quantifies the extent to which batch membership explains variability in the data.
Interpretation of ICC values:
- ICC close to 0: Little to no variance explained by batch; suggests minimal batch effect.
- ICC around 0.1-0.3: Small batch effect; may be acceptable depending on context.
- ICC around 0.3-0.5: Moderate batch effect; consider further investigation or correction.
- ICC above 0.5: Strong batch effect; likely requires correction to avoid confounding.

Marginal R² represents the variance explained by fixed effects (covariates)
while Conditional R² represents the variance explained by both fixed and random effects (batch + covariates).
